   3. F is strictly greater than P, establishing the multiplicative growth condition.
   4. The greatest common divisor of F and b equals 1, ensuring mutual primality.

In the classical Collatz (3n + 1) problem, these operational components are rigorously fixed: F = 3 (The Inflator), b = 1 (The Ballast), and P = 2 (The Reductor). The integer value k_n defines the reduction multiplicity power (the operational strength of the Reductor) at step n.
